-- Stocks in South Africa Climb For a Fourth Day in Five, Led By BHP Billiton
-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 2010-12-20T15:56:28Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-20/stocks-in-south-africa-climb-for-4th-day-in-five-led-by-anglogold-sasol.html
South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  advanced for the fourth day in five, gaining 101.45,
or 0.3 percent, to 31,732.52 at the 5 p.m. close in
Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  BHP Billiton Plc  (BIL SJ), the world’s biggest mining
company, snapped three days of losses, gaining 1.09 rand, or 0.4
percent, to 267.09 rand. Copper increased 1.1 percent to $9,157
a metric ton on the London Metal Exchange. Tin and zinc rose.
 Anglo American Plc  (AGL SJ), the diversified mining company that
makes up 10 percent of South Africa’s benchmark index, added 52
cents, or 0.2 percent, to 333.85 rand.  Gold Fields Ltd.  (GFI SJ), Africa’s second-largest producer
of the metal, added 1.07 rand, or 0.9 percent, to 122.79 rand,
paring its 3.3 percent drop on Dec. 17. Gold advanced as much as
1.2 percent to $1,388.38 an ounce.  AngloGold Ashanti Ltd.  (ANG
SJ), the world’s third-largest gold producer, gained the most
since Dec. 14, increasing 3.50 rand, or 1.1 percent, to 332.82
rand.  Simmer & Jack Mines Ltd.  (SIM SJ) jumped 3 cents, or 3.1
percent, to 1.01 rand.  Jasco Electronic Holdings Ltd.  (JSC SJ), a South African
telecommunications company, advanced the most since June 2009,
rising 17 cents, or 12 percent, to 1.55 rand. Jasco declared a
dividend of 3 cents a share for the six months ending Dec. 31,
it said in a regulatory statement today.  O-Line Holdings Ltd . (OLI SJ), a manufacturer of cable
ladders, increased to the highest level since October 2009,
gained 3 cents, or 3.2 percent, to 98 cents. The company said
that it has entered into negotiations that may affect its share
price.  Rare Holdings Ltd.  (RAR SJ), a South African maker of pipes
and valves, jumped to the highest in more than a month, gaining
7 cents, or 21 percent, to 41 cents. The company said it reached
an agreement to issue new shares to Stafric Investments and
Management Services (Pty) Ltd. at 40 cents a share, raising 40
million rand ($5.8 million).  Sasol Ltd.  (SOL SJ), the world’s biggest maker of motor
fuel from coal, climbed to highest closing level since Nov. 19,
adding 2.21 rand, or 0.7 percent, to 333.71 rand. The company
said it will pay C$1.05 billion ($1.04 billion) for a 50 percent
stake in Canada’s Talisman Energy Inc.’s shale gas assets.  To contact the reporter on this story:
